      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the earlier confusion; you are absolutely right, and I will focus strictly on the professional logistics and administrative causes for your Rotterdam hub's inventory shrinkage. The pattern of small, recurring variances like -8 and -6 units on high-value electronics is a classic sign of \"administrative lag\" combined with \"unit of measure (UoM) errors,\" rather than a goblin heist.\n\nHere is a professional analysis of the likely business causes for these discrepancies:\n\n**1. Unit of Measure (UoM) Mismatch**\nThis is the most common culprit for small variances in electronics. Did the system record \"1450\" as individual units, but the physical count was done in \"packs\" or \"sets\"? For example, if SKU-992-A comes in boxes of 10, a single box might be counted as 10 units in the system but logged as 1 item on a physical sheet, or vice versa. If the warehouse team manually entered counts without verifying the UoM flag, a difference of 8 units could easily result from counting 8 loose components instead of their full packaging.\n\n**2. Administrative Lag and Cycle Counting Errors",
